I absolutely love this tiny cozy place in Brooklyn! I was craving some really good Thai food and I’ve been to a couple of places where I didn’t like the Tom Yum soup or Pad Thai at all but I love this gem of a place.  Me and my boyfriend usually visit on Saturday/Sunday’s and the place wasn’t packed at all. You have the choice of sitting inside or outside which is fantastic and the whole atmosphere of the restaurant just transports you to Thailand.  The food was a bit on the sweeter side but I’m Indian so my spice levels are kind of high. I’ve tried both the Tom yum and Tom kha soups and both are fantastic although if you want a spicer one you should choose the Tom yum.  Noodles, rice and mains they have a wide variety and their starters are pretty delicious too. We had a special crab Rangoon which has a cream cheese filling inside and it was perfectly paired with some sweet chilli sauce. Don’t miss out on this place if you’re in the neighborhood for some really good Thai food!

I could not wait to write a review for this restaurant simply because the food is amazing. Let me give you a quick synopsis on how I stumbled upon this restaurant. So I went on to the Uber Eats application in search of a restaurant with great rice. I ordered the Khao Pad with shrimp and a order of Chicken Satay which came up to 24.50 plus the delivery tax. When the food arrived it was still hot,  but the meat wasn't sweating and soggy. The Khao Pad is fried rice with onions, scallions, carrots shaped like a sun and tomatoes which were prepared with jumbo shrimp.  Side note the shrimp was completely clean and split down the middle so it was cooked thoroughly. All in all the rice was perfectly seasoned and had a great taste, which is the reason why I ate the whole container in one sit in. Moving on to the Chicken Satay which is also known as grilled chicken on skewers. The chicken was well seasoned and tasted pretty simple even though it had a yellow tint as if it had been cooked in curry sauce. The Chicken was served with raw lettuce and shredded carrots along with two dipping sauces. One of the dipping sauces tastes like peanut juice with a hint of pepper, but it had the consistency of peanut butter mixed with oil. The second sauce looks like water with cut up vegetables in it, and it tasted like sweet vinegar . I didn't use either sauce on my food but I was very pleased with my meal and I feel like my money was well spent.

Would have given 5 stars if not for this: The Wine was a bit pricey and the glasses weren't filled so we asked to buy a bottle but was told we couldn't because they were on their last bottle. I came here with my friends for my birthday and overall had a great time. Loved that they offered 10% off for paying cash.
The food was delicious and the service quick.  The prices are appropriate for the area/cuisine.  I will certainly be returning here for more tasty things.
My wife and I were looking for a place to relax and eat and happened upon this gem. Food was great (pad Thai and some kind of chicken cashew Curry) and really nice atmosphere.
The food is terrible and the service is worst. Don't waste your time.

What a great experience. A family run restaurant with excellent service. The food is really fresh and my girlfriend who is vegetarian had plenty of options which is a must for us. Sticky mango rice is amazing !!!!
I ordered takeout. The food was awesome food and the hostess was very sweet. Can't wait to actually dine in.
Highly recommend their Pad Ki Mao for people who prefer spicy food.
I enjoyed my food
This place is awesome! The food was seasoned well and tasted great. I would reommend Corthaiyou to anyone  who likes thai cusine and wants something that is affordable.

Great addition to the neighborhood. Not overly Americanized thai food, they specialized in northern cuisine. Papaya salad Som Tum is pretty close to what they serve in Thailand. Other places that are in Kensington worth a shot and where I order takeout is Am Thai Bistro on Church Ave

Really quick and friendly service (I think one of the owners checked in on us at the end of our dinner). Top notch Thai food- seriously. As we were finishing up a party of 9 walked in without a res and they were willing to accommodate them.  I had the Kwei Thew Ped and it was one of the most savory, flavorful soup based dishes I've had. The lemon grass drink was a great refreshing palate cleanser. Cute ambiance with wood facade and a backyard (??). Will go again.

From good to bad: 1. My order was prepared quickly and well packaged for take-out. 2. The Tom Yum soup was pretty good. It's the first thing I order in any Thai place and I would get it again here. 3. My wife's beef pad see-ew was short on broccoli and suffered from blandness. 4. The baby back ribs in garlic sauce were cooked well but completely devoid of seasoning. The small container with sauce offered a reprieve from blandness, but with nary a hint of garlic. 5. Grilled porgy in banana leafs... sticky, covered with very hard to remove, inedible skin (scales not removed) and bland asf. The dish smelled like the leafs, but tasted like nothing. Definitely avoid this "special".  Sadly the common theme here is lack of seasoning and flavor, which is really sad for Thai cuisine. 2.5 stars
Food was delicious. I had the chicken pad Thai, and it really gets better as you eat it.  The drunken noodles are the bomb!!
